<sup>1</sup> Contains the Proto-Altaic dual suffix {{IPA|-/rʲV/}}: "both breasts" – "chest" – "heart".<br />
<sup>2</sup> Contains the Proto-Altaic singulative suffix -/nV/: "one breast".<br />
<sup>3</sup> Compare [[Baekje]] */turak/ "stone" (Blažek 2006).<br />
<sup>4</sup> This is in the Jurchen language. In modern Manchu it is ''usiha''.<br />
<sup>5</sup> This is disputed by Georg (2004),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/jbp/dia/2004/00000021/00000002/art00010?token=0058191b9d3ccda7f7e41225f406a5e2c6b4173483f3c255050576b34272c5f7b3d6d3f4e4b34a6eb76ca7f7 |title=Etymological Dictionary of the Altaic Languages (2003) |publisher=Ingentaconnect.com |date=2004-01-01 |accessdate=2013-06-18}}</ref> who states: "The traditional Tungusological reconstruction ''*yāsa'' [ = {{IPA|/jaːsa/}}] cannot be replaced by the nasal-initial one espoused here, needed for the comparison." However, Starostin (2005)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/jbp/dia/2005/00000022/00000002/art00008?token=00541ba51aae7dd8d6c573d257025255c232b465340514d3874747c4e7547543c7e386f642f466fad2e3 |title=Response to Stefan Georg's review of the Etymological Dictionary of the Altaic Languages |publisher=Ingentaconnect.com |date=2005-01-01 |accessdate=2013-06-18}}</ref> mentions evidence from several Tungusic languages cited by Starostin et al. (2003). Georg (2005)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/jbp/dia/2005/00000022/00000002/art00009?token=005418488f488b387e2a46762c47655d76702a252c2a766c7b673f7b2f267738703375686f4997755709 |title=ingentaconnect Reply |publisher=Ingentaconnect.com |date=2005-01-01 |accessdate=2013-06-18}}</ref> does not accept this, referring to Georg (1999/2000) and a then upcoming paper.<ref>Georg 2005</ref>

====Numerals and related words====
In the [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European family]], the [[Numeral (linguistics)|numerals]] are remarkably stable. This is a rather exceptional case; especially words for higher numbers are often borrowed wholesale. (Perhaps the most famous cases are Japanese and Korean, which have two complete sets of numerals each – one native, one Chinese.) Indeed, the Altaic numerals are less stable than the Indo-European ones, but nevertheless Starostin et al. (2003) reconstruct them as follows:

